Project findings

As shown in Figure 15, the largest increases in job access occur in the TAZs in closest proximity to US 29 BRT’s alignment. The addition of project increased the number of accessible jobs for the general population by 0.1 percent. Accessibility increases for the disadvantaged population are 0.3 percent. The following table summarizes the change in job accessibility for the general and disadvantaged populations in the study area.

Table 5. Project Finding

Measure 2020
Access to Jobs in Base (general population) 209,686.00
Access to Jobs in Build (general population) 209,877.00
Change in Access to Jobs (general population) 191.00
Access to Jobs in Base (disadvantaged population) 87,724.00
Access to Jobs in Build (disadvantaged population) 88,030.00
Change in Access to Jobs (disadvantaged population) 306.00
Change in Average Travel Time Per Trip (minutes) -0.38
Estimated Ridership 9,979.00
Estimated Existing Ridership (Estimated Ridership * 80%) 7,983.00
Total Estimated Travel Time Savings for Existing Transit Riders (Change in Average Travel Time Per Trip * Estimated Existing Ridership) -3,058.00
